ed States":"Champaign, Ohio, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","Sullivan, New Hampshire, United States":"Sullivan, New Hampshire, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","New Jersey":"New Jersey, Verenigde Staten van Amerika"},"en":{"1758–1820":"1758–1820","1750–1799":"1750–1799","1782–1852":"1782–1852","1785–Male":"1785–Deceased","1787–Male":"1787–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","11 April 1782":"11 April 1782","3 June 1799":"3 June 1799","1792":"1792","1791":"1791","1810":"1810","1799":"1799","1787":"1787","1820":"1820","1776":"1776","1852":"1852","1785":"1785","1750":"1750","1782":"1782","about 1785":"about 1785","1808":"1808","1758":"1758","Salem, New Jersey, United States":"Salem, New Jersey, United States","Charleston, South Carolina, United States":"Charleston, South Carolina, United States","Champaign, Ohio, United States":"Champaign, Ohio, United States","Sullivan, New Hampshire, United States":"Sullivan, New Hampshire, United States","New Jersey":"New Jersey, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>parker</i> ‘park-keeper’ (Old French <i>parquier</i>, <i>parchier</i>), an officer employed to look after deer and other game in a hunting park (see   Park   1). This surname is also very common among African Americans. It has also been recorded since medieval times in Ireland.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish names."],"variants":[{"name":"Parkman","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>park</i> ‘enclosure, game preserve, park’ (Old French <i>parc</i>) + <i>man</i>, sometimes for one living at or near such a place but probably more often denoting someone employed to look after after deer and other game in a hunting park; compare   Parker  .","occupational name denoting the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of someone called <i>Park</i> (see   Park   2)."]},{"name":"Parkerson","meanings":["English: from the occupational name   Parker   + patronymic <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Parkey","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): dialect pronunciation of   Parker  . <i>Parker</i> has a long history in Macclesfield, Manchester, and Bridgnorth."]},{"name":"Park","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Sang, Sung, Yong, Jung, Jong, Chan, Jae, Jin, Kwang, Kyung, Myung, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1352452,"age":18,"year":"1776","julianDay":2369731,"description":"Thomas Jefferson's American Declaration of Independence endorsed by Congress. Colonies declare independence.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1701451,"age":18,"year":"1776","julianDay":2369731,"title":"Battle of Sullivan's Island","description":"On June 28, 1776, the Battle of Sullivan's Island takes place on Sullivan's Island, South Carolina. Since it is so close to Charelston, the battle is sometimes referred to as the First Siege of Charleston. This is the first time that the Americans had a victory against a land and sea attack by the British.","url":"https://www.britishbattles.com/war-of-the-revolution-1775-to-1783/battle-of-sullivans-island/","urlTitle":"British Battles","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":135245